snippet.textDisplay:
I know we all see this whole idea of in home quarantine and 'lockdown' as something along the lines of devistarting and really emotionally cutting us off from life and others and sme really wonder how they are going to get through it. Maybe a bit of historical perspective to help us all realize just how bad we don't have it.


The idea of quarantine is nt new in the US and, at one time was practised pretty judiciously when other viruses and infections occurred, especially in the days before we had disinfectants, antibiotics, antivirals, air purifiers, particulate filters and filter material for masking, disposables such as gloves and masks and paper products and vaccines against many communicable diseases which were only ever controlled by quarantining as soon as cases were identified.


Things like measles and mumps, smallpox and and such ended up with bid signs being slapped on your door by public health officials warning the community not to approach not only if there was an active case in your home but if any members of your family had been exposed to an active case. Even post WW2 quarantining the public was still the main defense that public health had for controlling progression of a disease that could reach epidemic proportions. Even into the 1950's and dealing with the polio epidemic social distancing, not gathering in large numbers and when the disease was active in the community at home quarantine was still the way things went.


We are less familiar with the idea of guaratine now as technology and medicine improved so much into the 1960's and beyond and thing like vaccination programs. Smallpox was literally eradicated as were many other communicable diseases. We did more to protect communal water supplies and did away with things like typhoid and cholera epidemics. And vaccines became available to the public for most childhood disease we stopped seeing schools closed for the durations of outbreaks and families asked to remain at home except for essential needs and if your home had an active case, the town saw your food and supplies delivered to your property line and left for you to pick up, often not even approaching your front porch.


Imagine what the level of isolation was at times like this. Even into the 1960's not all homes had a private landline and there was no such things as internet or cable or mobile phones. In the times before TV there was radio, but even that was a relatively newer relief to families in quarantine then the pre WW2 eras. Until cable TV came along in the 70-80's than most people had to TV fare were whatever local stations their TV antenna could pick up and in some markets that might have been as little as 6 hours of programming a day. Before phone service was something pretty much everyone had, which was actually the early 70's, written word was still a major way to communicate and in most quarantines the Public health doctors feared communication of disease on paper and you were often restricted from sending you own written messages. If you needed to contact distant family or friends you often had to dictate a message across your yard to someone who would then communicate it by mail or telegram to those you wished t reach.


There was no way to get online and it a hangout or skype call where you could see the faces of others talking to you, or even having the luxury of your own phone that you could chat on as many hours as you liked, a yu may have had one land line in the home which you hared with others and in many places in the US whole town's shared partylines s that basically many families all shared the same phone connection meaning no one could selfishly hold the phone just for social chit chat.


When you get really ticked off at having to feel 'imprisoned' in your own home I would suggest people challenge themselves to a "Day in the Life of a 1980's Quarantine" and other then maybe a video running to document it for others,, try and see just how you would manage back then and how much better you have it now. Yes, it's an inconvenience most certainly but its not really all that bad.


Try unplugging your mobiles and getting off the net, and having to limit and make due with just what you have around your home for anything you want to decrease the boredom. And to that that you need to mimic as much as possible not have central heat and AC and hide all your paper products and do all your heightened cleaning by hand and then having to wash all the cloth materials you cleaned with rather than just disposing of them. You will find that , even in quarantines, some o the boredom is offset by the fact that there is more physical work to do then we have to do in our current times, but maybe we all need a dose of what its like not to be able to just grab a cell phone and talk to someone, or turn on a TV and lose ourselves in binge watching a series we missed or several movies we have been meaning to catch. NAd, of course, any gaming entertainment is probably going to be limited to card games or board games, if you have people in the home to play with.


Spend 24 hours in the shoes of those Americans that expected quarantine to happen on a regular basis almost every year and maybe we would be less likely to bemoan just how bad doing this in this day and age for a couple of weeks to see if we are able to have it get things under control.
